With the advent of the internet came an unprecedented ability to share information quicker and more accurately than ever before.
The evolution of services that facilitate this sharing of information have culminated today into a crowdsourced encyclopedia vaster than anything before (Wikipedia.org), and social sharing sites such as Twitter and Facebook that are an important means of communication today for most of the developed world.
On Twitter in particular, more voices are being heard than ever before with more than 500 million people generating over 340 million messages per day.\\

The usefulness of this wealth of interaction has been leveraged in the past to crunch hard problems (FoldIt) and digitize all books (ReCaptcha), and is proving increasinly useful to find information through social search.
Alongside these efforts, we aim to use the text shared on Twitter to detect important stories being reported by individual users and shared across the network.
We call this distributed news aggregation tool the \emph{storyfinder}.
After outlining the methods involved, we present the results of the storyfinder for one week of Twitter data surrounding the 2013 Boston Marathon.\\

\textbf{Partitioning Text:}\\

To begin analyzing the information being shared in large real-time texts, we first need to break this text down into the meaningful units of langauge.
We call these units phrases.
Here I present a brief description of the phrase partitioner of Williams et. al. \cite{williams-partitioner} which we rely on.\\

First we create a probability distribution of all possible phrases in a text based on frequency of appearance in that text.
We then go back and partition the same text using that probability distribution to find the optimal partition of phrases.

\textbf{Computing Entropy of Phrases}\\

The entropy of a phrase is computed within it's local context using Shannon entropy:
\[ E(p) = \sum _{c(p)} p \log p .\]

For a phrase, the value of entropy is limited by the frequency of appearance of the phrase. \\

\textbf{Computing Ambient Valence of Phrases}\\

The LabMT dataset provided by Dodds et. al. \cite{dodds-happiness} contains 10222 words with happiness scores on a 1 to 9 scale, averaged over 50 independent ratings through Mechanical Turk.
To extend the valence scores on words into scores on phrases, we compute the ambient valence of a phrase $p$ be averaging the scores of all the words surrounding this phrase for which we have scores.
% As was shown by Dodds et. al., this instrument is tunable to the removable of neutral words.
% We test this tunability on ambient phrase scoring by considering the correlation of the happiness timeseries on Twitter.
